Exercise 1.

After reading Doughnut Economics: Seven Ways To Think Like a 21st Century Economist, Dr. LC Sulla is set out to test empirically whether the Kuznets Curve and its environmental counterpart are verified in reality.

  • Classical Kuznets curve: at first, growth increases with inequality and then wealth “lifts everyone up”, reducing inequality.
    1
  • Environmental Kuznets Curve (EKC): at first growth increases at the expense of environmental degradation. When people have sufficient income, the economy shifts to a less environment-degrading one. That is, after a turning point “economic growth cleans up”.

As a first step to the analysis, Dr. Sulla is performing an exploratory analysis on the gathered data ( cf. df1.csv ) for year \(2010\) with the following variables collected from different countries: IncomeGroup, GDP_per_capita, CO2_emissions, Gini_pct, Population.

  1. Retrieve the country codes with the three highest Tukey depths when taking into account the three dimensionsGDP_per_capita, CO2_emissions_per_capita and the logit transformation of the Gini coefficient (which is essentially a measure of inequality defined in \((0,1)\) ).2. Which one of them is the median?
library(DepthProc)
df1 <- read.csv("df1.csv")

df1$Gini = sapply(df1$Gini, function(x)log(x/(1-x)))
depths <- depth(u=df1[,c(4,5,6)],method='Tukey')
df1[order(depths,decreasing = T)[1:6],]
  1. Focusing on those same dimensions, draw a bagplot matrix. Report the countries that are inside the bag of the GDP_per_capita versus CO2_emissions bagplot.3. Report which countries are outliers of such bagplot and remove them from the data set for the following exercises.

  1. Without the aforementioned outliers in the dataset, implement through a permutational a MANOVA test for the equality of the multivariate mean (using GDP_per_capita, CO2_emissions and logit(Gini) ) of the three groups of countries according to IncomeGroup, utilising the Wilks statistic4. Report the histogram of the Monte Carlo approximation of the permutational distribution of the test statistic, the resulting p-value of the test and your conclusion.
df1 <- df1[-outs.indices, ]
B <- 1e3
seed = 2024

fit <- manova(as.matrix(df1[, c(4,5,6)]) ~ df1$IncomeGroup)
summary.manova(fit,test="Wilks") 
T0 <- -summary.manova(fit,test="Wilks")$stats[1,2]

set.seed(seed)
T_stat <- numeric(B)
n <- dim(df1)[1]

for(perm in 1:B){
  # choose random permutation
  permutation <- sample(1:n)
  income.group.perm <- df1$IncomeGroup[permutation]
  fit.perm <- manova(as.matrix(df1[, c(4,5,6)]) ~ income.group.perm)
  T_stat[perm] <- -summary.manova(fit.perm,test="Wilks")$stats[1,2]
}
hist(T_stat,xlim=range(c(T_stat,T0)),breaks=30)
abline(v=T0,col=3,lwd=2)

Exercise 2

After some other touches to the data set (df2.csv), Dr. Sulla is ready to test for the existence of the Kuznets and the Environmental Kuznets curve.
5


  1. Implement a quadratic fit utilising raw polynomials for the classical Kuznets curve (CO2_emissions_per_capita vs GDP_per_capita) and one for the Environmental Kuznets Curve (EKC) (logit(Gini) vs GDP_per_capita). Provide a plot of the regression lines with parametric pointwise parametric prediction invervals and a table summarising the coefficients. Comment the results: are they coherent with the economic theory?
logit <- function(x){log(x/(1-x))}
df2 <- read.csv("df2.csv")
names(df2)
m_quad=lm(I(sapply(Gini, logit)) ~ GDP_per_capita + I(GDP_per_capita^2), data=df2)
summary(m_quad)
gdp.grid <- seq(min(df2$GDP_per_capita), max(df2$GDP_per_capita), length.out=100)

preds=predict(m_quad,list(GDP_per_capita=gdp.grid),se=T)
se.bands=cbind(preds$fit +2* preds$se.fit ,preds$fit -2* preds$se.fit)

plot(df2$GDP_per_capita ,sapply(df2$Gini, logit) ,xlim=range(gdp.grid) ,cex =.5, col =" darkgrey ",main='Gini vs GDP per capita')
lines(gdp.grid, preds$fit ,lwd =2, col =" blue")
matlines (gdp.grid ,se.bands ,lwd =1, col =" blue",lty =3)

m_quad=lm(CO2_emissions ~ GDP_per_capita + I(GDP_per_capita^2), data=df2)
summary(m_quad)
gdp.grid <- seq(min(df2$GDP_per_capita), max(df2$GDP_per_capita), length.out=100)

preds=predict(m_quad,list(GDP_per_capita=gdp.grid),se=T)
se.bands=cbind(preds$fit +2* preds$se.fit ,preds$fit -2* preds$se.fit)

plot(df2$GDP_per_capita ,df2$CO2_emissions,xlim=range(gdp.grid) ,cex =.5, col =" darkgrey ",main='CO2 vs GDP per capita')
lines(gdp.grid, preds$fit ,lwd =2, col =" blue")
matlines (gdp.grid ,se.bands ,lwd =1, col =" blue",lty =3)

library(conformalInference)
lm_train = lm.funs(intercept = T)$train.fun
lm_predict = lm.funs(intercept = T)$predict.fun

design_matrix = matrix(poly(df2$GDP_per_capita,degree=2,raw=T), ncol=2)

  1. For the classical Kuznets curve, knowing that the Gini coefficient is a proportion, fit the following GAM : \[ logit(Gini) = \sum_{g \in \mathcal{G}} \beta_{g} + \beta_1 f(GDP) \] where \(\mathcal{G}\) = {Low income, Medium income, High income}, \(f(GDP)\) is a quadratic B-spline with one knot on GDP_per_capita\(=30000\). Provide a table summarising the coefficients of the regression, including a comment on statistical significance.
library(splines)
m3 <- lm(I(sapply(Gini, logit)) ~ IncomeGroup + splines::bs(GDP_per_capita, degree=2, knots=c(30000)), data=df2)
new_data = data.frame(IncomeGroup=rep("High income",100), GDP_per_capita=seq(min(df2$GDP_per_capita), max(df2$GDP_per_capita), length.out=100))
preds=predict(m3,new_data,se=T)
se.bands=cbind(preds$fit +2* preds$se.fit ,preds$fit -2* preds$se.fit)

with(df2, plot(GDP_per_capita ,sapply(Gini, logit) ,xlim=range(new_data$GDP_per_capita) ,cex =.5, col =" darkgrey " ))
lines(new_data$GDP_per_capita ,preds$fit ,lwd =2, col =" blue")
matlines(new_data$GDP_per_capita, se.bands ,lwd =1, col =" blue",lty =3)

  1. With a Bootstrap approach, provide the a reverse percentile confidence interval for the prediction of the model at GDP_per_capita\(=20000\) and IncomeGroup$=High Income
res.estimate <- m3$residuals
fitted <- m3$fitted.values
T0 <- predict(m3, newdata=list(GDP_per_capita=20000, IncomeGroup="High income"))

T.boot <- numeric(B)
attach(df2)
set.seed(2024)

for (b in 1:B){
  boot <- sample(1:length(m3$residuals), replace=T)
  res.boot <- res.estimate[boot]
  m3boot <- lm(I(fitted+ res.boot)~ IncomeGroup + bs(GDP_per_capita, degree=2, knots=c(30000)))
  T.boot[b] <-  predict(m3boot, newdata=list(GDP_per_capita=20000, IncomeGroup="High income"))
}
detach(df2)
alpha <- 0.05
right.quantile <- quantile(T.boot, 1 - alpha/2)
left.quantile  <- quantile(T.boot, alpha/2)

CI.RP <- c(T0 - (right.quantile - T0), T0 - (left.quantile - T0))
CI.RP

  1. Provide the (point-wise) \(\alpha=0.1\)-trimmed mean of each group. 6. Add them the last plot. Calculate the pointwise p-value of a permutation test using as test statistic the difference of the pointwise \(\alpha=0.1\)-trimmed means of both groups and interpret your results. In this case, use \(B=100\).
plot(f_data[-fbp$ID_outliers]) 
mean.high <- apply(df.func[df.func$IncomeGroup=="High income", -c(1,2)], MARGIN=2, FUN=function(x){mean(x, trim=.1)})
lines(time, mean.high,col="black")
mean.low <- apply(df.func[df.func$IncomeGroup=="Low income", -c(1,2)], MARGIN=2, FUN=function(x){mean(x, trim=.1)})
lines(time, mean.low,col="black")

uniperm=function(tindex,B=100){
  data <- df.func[, c(2,tindex+2)]
  n <- dim(data)[1]
  Tperm <- numeric(B)
  mean.high.pw <- mean(data[data$IncomeGroup=="High income", -1], trim=.1)  
  mean.low.pw <- mean(data[data$IncomeGroup=="Low income", -1], trim=.1)
  t0 <- sqrt((mean.high.pw- mean.low.pw)**2)

  for(index in 1:B){
    perm <- sample(1:n, replace = F)
    dfperm <- data
    dfperm[, -1] <- data[perm, -1]
    mean.high.perm <- mean(dfperm[dfperm$IncomeGroup=="High income", -1], trim=.1)
    mean.low.perm <- mean(dfperm[dfperm$IncomeGroup=="Low income", -1], trim=.1)
  Tperm[index] <- sqrt((mean.high.perm - mean.low.perm)**2)
  }
  return(sum(Tperm>=t0)/B)
}

pval.fun=numeric(length(time))
for(index in 1:length(time)){
  set.seed(2024)
  pval.fun[index]=uniperm(index)
}

plot(time, pval.fun, ylim=c(0,1))

  1. Following the logic of the EKC, high and low income countries should different C02_emissions. To see whether this is verified in the C02_emissions measured along time, perform a global permutation test for the equality of both functional \(\alpha\)-trimmed means, using as test statistic the \(L2\) distance between the \(\alpha\)-trimmed means (built as in Exercise \(1\)) of both groups. You can approximate it with the euclidean distance of the discretely sampled (\(100\) obs.) curves.
euclidean <- function(a, b) sqrt(sum((a - b)^2))
T0 <- euclidean(mean.high, mean.low)
n <- dim(df.func)[1]
B <- 1000
Tperm <- numeric(B)
set.seed(2024)
for (b in 1:B){
  perm <- sample(1:n, replace = F)
  dfperm <- df.func
  dfperm[, -c(1,2)] <- df.func[perm, -c(1,2)]
  mean.high.perm <- apply(dfperm[dfperm$IncomeGroup=="High income", -c(1,2)], MARGIN=2, FUN=function(x){mean(x, trim=.1)})
  mean.low.perm <- apply(dfperm[dfperm$IncomeGroup=="Low income", -c(1,2)], MARGIN=2, FUN=function(x){mean(x, trim=.1)})
  Tperm[b] <- euclidean(mean.high.perm, mean.low.perm)
}
sum(Tperm>=T0)/B
